metadata.name: Geode #160
metadata.description:
A single seed shape is chosen from 13, and placed onto the plane. At every step, a copy of this seed is laid edge-to-edge adjacent to an existing shape, without causing any overlaps. This copy is colored based on the edge it shares with the existing shape. The process continues until the animation completes.

New shapes are placed closest to a moving target. In some mints, this target is slow moving, causing new shapes to expand radially from the seed. In other mints, this target races around, causing new shapes to chase it. 

Each of the 13 shapes forms different patterns under different circumstances. Not all patterns will be explored.

Controls:
  - SPACE: Pause/unpause the animation.
  - ENTER: Skip the animation.
  - R: Restart the animation.

URL Params:
  - "preview=1": Skip the animation.
  - "flex=1": Adapt the boundaries to the size of the window.
  - ‚Äúslow=1‚Äù: Draw only one shape per frame.

metadata.name: Versus in Motion #143
metadata.description:
"Versus in Motion" is an animated version, a successor of original "Versus" collection
https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/21865

Includes all features of "Versus" (resolution levels, switchable orientation, etc) plus it's animated (obviously) and interactive
- You can stop & start animation at any time by pressing the spacebar
- You may click (or click & drag) while in animation or not, to modify the current artwork

Animation cycle is actually a transition between a "full" and an "empty" state that symbolizes the transition between existence, non-existence,  prosperity & decline and the evolution and progress in general as a result of time passage..

All are pure code, shapes and curves that processed in a custom fragment glsl (webgl) shader using a relative "advanced" developed mixing technique.

CONTROLS

KEYS:

- 1-4: Set resolution from 1x to 4x of the current dimension (possibly slower performance in higher values)
- S: Save a png file with the current resolution

- P: Change orientation to Portrait with aspect ratio 0.75 (useful eg. for printing)
- L: Change orientation to Landscape with ratio 4/3  (1.333..)
- O: Original orientation. That is the default Square (box)
  Due to some 1:1 ratio sensitive calculations, rendering output may differ when switching 
  orientations

  For animation:
- Spacebar: toggle animation (on/off)
- R: Reset the center of animation (if has been modified with click or drag)

MOUSE:

- Click (or Click & Drag) to set the center of animation

----
Made with p5js and custom shaders

¬© Dec. 2022  @Uniray_net | uniray.net

metadata.name: Hex-a-Sketch #10
metadata.description:
Truchet tiling with hexagons, drawn with three amounts of sketchiness in p5.js.  I had a lot of fun with this!  I love how it often looks like pastels, and sometimes like crayons.  Sometimes it reminds me of basket weaves or a quilt, or a warm sweater.  The super-sketchy can look chaotic, like it's trying to jump off the page, but if it weren't being made sketchy, then all the tiling would sync together in one form.  The foreground says, "look at me!" But then you notice the background with its nuance and depth.  It's like a dance between the two - the yin and the yang.  

I love sharing what I‚Äôve learned about gen art and inspiring others on my YouTube channel, Steve‚Äôs Makerspace.

press 2 - 5 to increase pixel density
press s to save a png

Resize goes back to pixel density 1.

metadata.name: Brinco #102
metadata.description:
As slinkies rise and sway through flurries of confetti, sometimes this play is focused and orderly. At other times, they crowd together riotously, conspiring to sneak off the sides altogether.

"Brinco" (Portuguese for "I play") is about celebrating finding joy in my creative pursuits again; about not overthinking it and simply following what makes me happy.

Creative joy can be capricious, leaving us when we need it the most. We hope we can relate to our artistic practice in a positive way, tapping into what feels like a bottomless source of energy and excitement. But sometimes when life becomes overwhelming, what gave you energy before now feels hollow and rote‚Äîjust one more thing sapping at you, and an emptiness where creative passion once resided.

For over a year, I've been sitting in this shadow. Until one day, I sat down and started tinkering‚Ä¶ and for the first time in such a long time, I started to feel the spark.

I hope that viewers and collectors feel that same spark of joy and playfulness when seeing these pieces that I've felt creating them.

Press "s"/"S" to save a PNG at the current size and press "h"/"H" to save a high resolution version.

metadata.name: odium #47
metadata.description:
The idea behind "odium" is to mix the two previous works to create a new art, which maintains similarities with the previous projects, but also with its differences and peculiarities.

"odium" is based on an algorithm that I've been exploring since the "radium" and "illusions" projects. So this is the last of the series.

It is composed by with grainy/noise and flowfields, creating a glitch effect as it is finishing to render.
"odium" have random colormaps instead a configured palette system, patterns of growth and plays with randomized blendModes and colorModes, 
and I name it "odium"  because the form it grows and glitch reminds me how the hate sometimes slowly consume the mind.

This is a project made in p5.js


Omar Lobato, 04/29/2022.

metadata.name: ecolog√≠as - A #590
metadata.description:
ecolog√≠as - A

lines are a metaphor for the communication all species engage in. We as humans have a need to leave traces - stories - that others can read and learn from. What will be the traces machines want to leave? This piece employs sinusoidal signals drawn with lines as a simple metaphor for every trace and every language, for every message and every communication.

ecolog√≠as-A is an entity that is part of a broader ecology. Released on occasion of the show "Unbound - Ecology in the Age of Machines" at Unit London. The data generated by this entity is read by a different piece minted on Ethereum, creating a link between Tezos and Ethereum, a metaphor for an ecology of blockchains.

it shares a common element with two other works released on fxhash: ecolog√≠as B and ecolog√≠as C, all of them contributing data to aforementioned pieces.

read more at https://www.iillucid.com/ecologias

15% of primary sales are donated to institutions working towards improving biodiversity and environmental efforts.

metadata.name: Refrigerators and Wordsworth #22
metadata.description:
****
Haikus are easy
But sometimes don‚Äôt make sense
Refrigerator
****

DISCLAIMER: Programmatic syllable counting is a difficult problem. Occasionally, this work will generate sentences with one too many or one too few syllables. We have tried to make the syllable counting algorithm as robust as possible, but, due to the quirks of the English language, there will always be more cases that miscount. (And if you get 6 instead of 5, it‚Äôs value for money).

Originally made for January 28th, with the prompt ‚ÄúGenerative Poetry‚Äù, this is a complete overhaul of the original throwaway Genuary project (https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/24355) for #genuary32nd. This ground up rebuild features new backgrounds, a new method of Haiku generation, and a brand-new syllable counting function. 

The Haikus are generated using a Markov Chain, which creates sentences based on a large database of haikus. The Markov Chain Method guarantees that the generated strings are locally sensible (as in, adjacent words will make sense together), however, the whole string won‚Äôt necessarily make sense. We feel that this whimsical sentence structure somewhat accents the style of the haiku, by providing (accidentally) artistic phrases. Afterwards, the strings are screened with a homemade syllable counter, which attempts to guarantee a 5-7-5 structure of the Haiku. The generated haiku is then displayed in a field of letters, with various color palettes and animations possible, which are displayed as fxHash Features. Try and collect the Legendary Matrix + Rain combo!

Credits to xiboon, and his excellent Markov Chain library, kurwov (https://github.com/xiboon/kurwov). This framework forms the backbone of the generation. The haikus database was taken from https://github.com/herval/haikuzao/blob/master/inputs/haiku.txt and https://github.com/sballas8/PoetRNN/blob/master/data/haikus.csv , and then cleaned by us.
